    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-22T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-22T16:00:00-05:00" n="666"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d666">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 654.119/299b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SPA1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stovall</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-22T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 22, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1960. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_DEL1">Dresel</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 26. Further referring to your No. 35, Legation 3362, May 14, 6 p.m.<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d666fn1">Not printed.</note> Five ships flying American flag
                    aggregating over 30,000 tons dead weight have sailed for a French port with
                    grain for Swiss use. This includes the two vessels mentioned in Department’s
                    1846, May 3, 6 p.m. All five ships have been sent forward under the convoy
                    system described in Department 1846. In addition to these vessels the Norwegian
                    steamer mentioned in our No. 24<note n="1" xml:id="d666fn2">Not printed.</note>
                    is loading a cargo of foodstuffs, approximately 3,700 tons to be barley and the
                    balance lard. Two other ships under the American flag have been allocated for
                    Swiss use and question of most expedient method of dispatching them is now being
                    worked out. You are authorized to make such use of the foregoing information as
                    you see fit.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
